<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title><%= pageTitle %> – Art of the Orient</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css?v=2">
</head>
<body>
  <%- include('partials/header', { headerClass, pageTitle }) %>
  <%- include('partials/page-wrap-start') %>
  <main class="main">
    <h2 class="gallery-title"><%= pageTitle %></h2>
    <section class="section-text section-text-full">
      <p>Rinpa is perhaps the most immediately recognizable of all Japanese painting schools — a tradition of breathtaking decorative splendor characterized by bold, flat areas of brilliant mineral pigment, lavish application of gold and silver leaf, and a compositional approach that prioritizes pattern, rhythm, and two-dimensional surface beauty over spatial illusionism or narrative content — and yet it is also one of the most intellectually sophisticated, its apparent simplicity concealing a deep engagement with the Japanese literary and poetic tradition that rewards the attentive viewer with layer upon layer of allusion and meaning. Founded in the early seventeenth century by Tawaraya Sōtatsu, whose Wind God and Thunder God screens remain the school's defining masterpiece, and codified and extended by Ogata Kōrin in the early eighteenth century — from whose name the school takes its suffix rin — Rinpa was not a formal academy with a continuous lineage of master and student but rather a tradition perpetuated through admiration and deliberate reinterpretation, each generation of artists returning to the works of their predecessors and producing their own responses to them in a creative dialogue that stretched across two centuries. The school's subjects were drawn almost exclusively from the natural world and the classical Japanese literary canon — irises, plum blossoms, maples, waves, grasses, and the imagery of the imperial poetry anthologies — rendered with a stylization so extreme that individual flowers or waves become almost abstract, reduced to their essential visual gesture and presented against grounds of gold or silver leaf that dissolve any sense of earthly setting and place the subject in a realm of pure aesthetic experience. Rinpa painting was produced primarily for the aristocratic and wealthy merchant classes of Kyoto, and its works — screens, hanging scrolls, fans, lacquerware, and textiles — represent some of the most purely beautiful objects ever made in Japan.</p>
    </section>
  </main>
  <%- include('partials/page-wrap-end') %>
  <script src="/js/nav.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
